How to increment a Map value in Java:

You can increment a Map value by using the Map.get() method to get the current value, increment it, and then use Map.put() to set the new value. Here's an example:

```java
Map<String, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();
String word = "example";
Integer count = freq.get(word);
if (count == null) {
    freq.put(word, 1);
} else {
    freq.put(word, count + 1);
}
```

In this code, if the word is not already in the map, it is added with a count of 1. If the word is already in the map, its count is incremented by 1.

Java static attributes in an abstract class:

You can't override static methods in Java. Static methods belong to the class, not to instances of the class. Therefore, you can't override static methods in a subclass.

In your case, you're trying to set static attributes in an abstract class, which is not possible. The attributes 'name' and 'code' should be instance attributes, not static ones.

Here's how you can modify your code:

```java
public abstract class Cow {
    private String name;
    private String code;

    // getters and setters
    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public String getCode() {
        return code;
    }

    public void setCode(String code) {
        this.code = code;
    }
}

public class Milk extends Cow {
    static {
        Milk milk = new Milk();
        milk.setName("asdmilk");
        milk.setCode("KDDFA");
    }
}
```

In this code, 'name' and 'code' are instance attributes of the Milk class, so you can override the setters and getters in the Milk class. The static block in the Milk class sets the 'name' and 'code' attributes of a new Milk instance.

